y june   in san francisco calif jeremy stoppelman cofounder and ceo and director of yelp the crowdsourced review site is seen at crissy field with his dog darwin on tuesday june   in san francisco calif photo russell yip the chronicle image  of  jeremy stoppelman cofounder and ceo and director of yelp the crowdsourced review site is seen at crissy field with his dog darwin on tuesday june   in san francisco calif jeremy stoppelman cofounder and ceo and director of yelp the crowdsourced review site is seen at crissy field with his dog darwin on tuesday june   in san francisco calif photo russell yip the chronicle yelps jeremy stoppelman a profile    back to gallery jeremy stoppelman was on a conference call with venture capitalists when an assistant slipped him a note steve jobs is on the line stoppelman quietly left the room at yelp headquarters in downtown san francisco it was january  and google wanted to buy yelp the online crowdsourced review site on the phone jobs urged stoppelman who revered the apple chief as a visionary to stay independent and not sell out to google jobs was not a fan of google and had accused the search giant of stealing apples smartphone and tablet technology at that point we had already turned down google stoppelman said but steve liked yelp and wanted to make sure about google it was a moment where i said this is crazy what just happened  latest news videos for stoppelman who is  and cofounded yelp in october  the crazy moments have only continued after his company went public this spring when the young entrepreneur pushed the button to ring the opening bell on the new york stock exchange stoppelman received another call  this one from president obama congratulating him today yelp has a market capitalization of about  billion and stoppelmans  percent stake is valued at more than  million the company which started in san francisco as a vague idea about local now has  million unique monthly visitors and has expanded to  countries stoppelman is an undisputed junior titan of silicon valley soughtafter nerd he also has the canonical startup story he was the kid who loved to tinker who inadvertently blew a few things up and charred the walls with his experiments who learned programming in middle school earned his bachelors degree in computer engineering and then headed west  arriving in san francisco at the start of the dotcom boom he was the kid who became a soughtafter nerd and was  after his second job out of college  given  million to sit around a soma loft with a dozen people and a dog and dream up the next big thing the rule in the incubator was that wed play around and come up with crazy ideas said max levchin a ukraineborn computer scientist who cofounded the online payment system paypal where stoppelman worked as his second job out of college it was a hacker commune and the idea was to build great products levchin whose paypal was sold to ebay for  billion in  remembers the day stoppelman and another former paypal engineer russ simmons landed on the concept that would become yelp it was my th birthday and we were at the slanted door in the ferry building levchin said jeremy and russ had been talking about doing something with local review or local search and were asking questions like how do you get your friends to help you find the best plumber or doctor or nicest restaurant close by over lunch i could see russ and jeremy at the other end of the table just scheming after lunch they said they thought theyd figured it out ranking of businesses returning to the incubator on mission near third street levchin listened as stoppelman and simmons explained their inchoate idea of an email type of product where you ask your friends to help you come up with a ranking of businesses i thought it might work but it might not levchin said i backed them because i believed in russ and jeremy russ is an amazing developer and engineer and jeremy is just really smart and really tenacious with a lot of good stubbornness their idea was good but of course it was not what yelp ended up being which is very common with startups elon musk another paypal founder said he always considered yelp a cool idea musk had done something similar with a company called zip which he founded after dropping out of stanford graduate school to provide local online content to news organizations someone needed to do user reviews right said musk who went on to run tesla motors and cofound spacex which recently made history by having the first commercial spaceship complete a mission to the international space station effectively yelp is fulfilling a much better function than the yellow pages ever did musk said what jeremy did was come up with an unmet need to know about local businesses and services stoppelman who spent his early childhood in arlington va before his family moved to nearby mclean  his middle school was next to cia headquarters  said his interest in computers started in the fifth grade his mother lynn was an english teacher before she began a marketing business out of their home and his father john was a securities lawyer i think my dad did legal work for someone who had a packard bell  and they couldnt pay him so they gave him a computer stoppelman said sitting in a yelp conference room his vizsla named darwin at his side i was initially not allowed to touch it but that didnt last long i started tinkering with it and there were many times i screwed up the computer he got his own personal computer an amiga  when he was in the th grade and he was soon convinced that hed be a video game programmer when he grew up in high school he took programming classes in turbo pascal a software development system but the young stoppelman was equally interested in business and investing his father took small companies public and talked about stocks jeremy was  when he opened a schwab account and bought stocks with money earned mowing lawns or picking up pinecones when he arrived at the university of illinois he was interested in both finance and engineering he thought the business majors looked like they were having fun and the engineering majors looked like they were enduring torture he chose engineering and graduated in  arriving in the valley i was interviewing for jobs really as the bubble was getting started stoppelman said when he came out for an interview at a startup calledhome network a highspeed cable internet service he was struck by what he saw driving to the interview i was driving down highway  and id see these billboards for engineering tools like fpga an integrated circuit i thought this is a very hardcore place if people can afford billboards to advertise esoteric technologies that the average person would have no clue about within three weeks of being hired as a software engineer athome hed finished his work and found there was nothing else for him to do id go to my boss and say i was done hed say ok come back at  id come back and hed be gone it was a messedup company he stayed for four months all the while having his phone ring every day with recruiters i thought it was stupid to be with a big company stoppelman said i found my way to xcom the precursor to paypal where i interviewed with elon musk i didnt know these guys existed yet the yearold ceo this senior guy who has the crazy twinkle in his eye and hes telling me how his company is going to take down visa and mastercard id just never seen this before i thought of companies as big organizations that hired grayhaired ceos i was like whoa i want to learn from this guy so i ended up as the third engineer hired i stayed for   years when ebay purchased paypal stoppelman was ready for something different and he enrolled at harvard business school i came back to san francisco for the summer after my first year at harvard and was originally going to work for peter thiel the third paypal founder who had started a hedge fund called clarium capital we had been in touch and he said well find something for you to do so i went to his office and was filling out paperwork and peter said i was talking to max levchin and he has this new incubator thing brewing so i went over to  mission and max said great hang out here just brainstorm until you come up with something  stoppelman had every intention of returning to harvard in the fall jeremy was doing well in business school and his goal was to get under his belt the basics of business theory so he could be a wellrounded ceo to start his own company levchin recalled but when jeremy and russ had this idea that came together over my birthday lunch i said to jeremy you can hit the snooze button on the alarm clock of life or this can be the big alarm i told him he was ready and that this was a huge opportunity that  if he hit the snooze button  it would go away stoppelman said when max committed  million to us to basically two guys with an idea we had our are you for real or are you a phony moment stoppelman dropped out of harvard when yelp was started in  it was a social network built around asking friends for recommendations we got some early press on it stoppelman said but mostly people said its a cool concept but in practice its still easier just to email your friends directly while disappointed stoppelman and simmons began to look at how people had used the new site they landed on something interesting a change in plans we had added a feature literally as an afterthought stoppelman said russ asked me should we have a way people can write a review without being asked a question i said sure no one is going to use it but sure tuck it in there what we found after the failed launch was that writing reviews was popular we realized we had missed something there we began to build a new site that was all about making review writing fun the new yelp was launched in february  and began to take off immediately by june  it had  million unique visitors per month the site became popular in san francisco but then came the question of scalability stoppelman recalled people told us oh this will work in san francisco but not in a place like new york  yelp was rolled out in boston then chicago then los angeles and new york very early on they hit on the idea of a yelp elite squad where the most prolific yelpers were invited to social events the gatherings held sometimes once a week at bars and restaurants turned an online experience into a community of like minds the problem yelp faces today stoppelman noted is the same problem that google faces in its rankings several lawsuits have been filed by business owners against yelp reviewers and allegations of illegitimate reviews have dogged the company you are going to have people who are unhappy with the reviews or the placement stoppelman said rest assured our engineers are working every day to make sure reviews are unbiased and accurate daily routine unchanged on a recent day stoppelman who is unmarried and lives in the marina heads out on a walk along crissy field with darwin in slimfitting jeans slim blazer a checked buttondown and aviator shades he said that while his life is dotted with crazy moments  the calls from steve jobs or the president  his daily existence hasnt changed much his small desk at work is set in the midst of everyone elses he still likes checking out new bars and restaurants is a voracious reader of nonfiction a recent book was moonwalking with einstein the art and science of remembering everything and hes taking an online course to learn how to play the guitar his yearold brother michael is vice president of engineering at yelp and his mother was recently out for a visit his father died in  walking along the windswept path of crissy field stoppelman said he is looking now at how big yelp can be we are a successful us company but can we be global will the things that work here work in japan in china they all represent a different challenge looking out at the sweeping golden gate bridge stoppelman said as a kid i harbored this fantasy of starting a company i looked at the entrepreneur column in forbes i looked at it every month and thought i want to be that guy  the day yelp went public is a day hell never forget it was this euphoric feeling of pushing the button to turn on the bell and it was like that moment on the roller coaster going chaching chaching chaching and then im on squawk box and jim cramer is yelling at me and three panelists are hitting me with questions it was high stress but fun my mom was up there with me on the platform she was pretty fired up i dont know if it gets much better than that julian guthrie is a san francisco chronicle staff writer email jguthriesfchroniclecom latest from the sfgate homepageclick below for the top news from around the bay area and beyond sign up for our newsletters to be the first to learn about breaking news and more go to sign in and manage profile at the top of the page health care vote hollywood and dc respond on twitter after skinny repeal fails schumer was on the verge of tears speaking about mccain the night john mccain killed the gops healthcare fight morford mccain is still not a hero trump slams ‘ republicans and  democrats’ in tweet the trump presidency trump pushes out priebus names dhs kelly wh chief of staff trump now reportedly wants a general to be his chief of staff priebus takes his turn on the trump administration hot seat latest news bay area court interpreters hold walkout over pay dispute sf carjacking linked to vehicle arson fire trump roasted with epic ny post cover evoking survivor judge rejects ghost ship fire defendant’s bail request calif shark attack survivor recalls fighting off beast calif is growing eight times as much pot as needed  suspects arrested in car east bay burglary spree woman attacked and robbed on muni bus by four assailants tech ceos before and after they made it big bezos look has changed drastically since he started amazon the richest people in the bay area according to forbes musk risks missing t