versation with the yelp ceo who turns  this novemberhe is himself an avid yelper reviewing under the profile name big papa he has waxed enthusiastic over the renaissance salon in his current hometown of san francisco “my last haircut generated mucho complimentos”  and panned frankfurt’s airport an “authentic interpretation of dante’s inferno” among the happiest discoveries he has made by perusing yelp reviews is the existence of the seward street slides in san francisco’s castro district “it’s basically these two concrete slides in a quiet residential neighborhood” he says “you zip down them sitting on top of flattened cardboard boxes i’d be curious to learn the history of these slides because they’re like not at all safe”he initially resisted the push to name his company yelp because to him it sounded like “a sad cry for help” he preferred the name yocal rhyming with “local” he grew up in the virginia suburbs of washington dc the son of a securities lawyer and a teacher and attended langley high school just down the road from the headquarters of the cia among his schoolmates were a son of antonin scalia’s and some kids who were curiously vague about what their parents did for a livinghe is—notwithstanding the fact that google’s autocomplete function suggests the words “jeremy stoppelman indian” when you enter his name into the search field—a jewish american of european ancestry who attended a reform temple as a child and had a bar mitzvah he attributes the frequent misperception of his ethnicity to his “black hair and dark skin tone”he played tennis as a youth and was often told that he looked like pete samprashis first computer—his family’s actually—was an amiga  a littleremembered lates highend pc with “unbelievable sound and graphics capabilities” that to this day he feels doesn’t get its duehis younger brother michael is yelp’s vice president in charge of engineering his older brother andy two years his senior died abruptly on the eve of his highschool graduation in  of a rare heartrhythm disorder that experience jeremy says made him realize that “life is very short and you have to make the most of it”he is frequently vilified by critics who claim that yelp is a protection racket whose sales representatives shake down smallbusiness owners offering better placement of positive reviews andor the burying of negative reviews in exchange for ad purchases—a charge that stoppelman flatly denies noting that all the lawsuits brought against yelp to this effect have been dismissedhe was called a “scumbag” a “dick” and “full of shit” among other things when he participated in a reddit ask me anything session last year he did not respond in kindhe accepts the invective hurled his way as the cost of creating a “disruptive gamechanging service or product” likening the heat yelp takes to that felt by airbnb visàvis the hotel industry and uber visàvis the taxicab industryhe has met three current or former heads of state two us presidents barack obama and bill clinton and the taoiseach of ireland enda kennyby anonymousreply  thats uhmaaaaazingby anonymousreply  purple gang by anonymousreply  yelp sucks i reported a place as being closed out of business three times over a period of two months and they still are showing it as open and they even posted reviews from people who say that its closed theyre either morons or seriously understaffedby anonymousreply  since when is extortion a revolutionary productyelp is worse than the mobby anonymousreply  since when should i give a shit what some visiting rube from cleveland cares about a restaurant yelp is beyond worthlessby anonymousreply  itll never be as stylish as little edies revolutionary costumeby anonymousreply  new reply unread privacyterms  the datalounge® is   by mediapolis inc all rights reserved ×close get thedl delivered  the latest on your favorite topics delivered to your email inbox twice a week its easy to subscribe and unsubscribe when you want to give it a try its free so why 